weeks with either no printing available at all for some or all staff
(variable) or printing that is not effective (i.e 45 mins to print 2
documents today it can take a minimum of 5 minutes to print a single black
and white page).

We have limited access to printers as it is; it's an incredibly busy time
for us and the impact on workload is now substantial. Not to mention the
bottle-neck it is creating with jobs that can't be done. Confidential
documents, such as employment contracts, require a member of staff to wait
for the printing for up to 45 mins.

It's been logged a number of times through email and by phone over the last
two weeks. We've been told there will be an update by 12 today but
'update', not resolved.

We have a further issue with A2C which for some reason was removed from our
systems/computers. It has been on and in use throughout the exam season as
this is how we make entries so this has happened since then.

I know Nik Forrest has worked with Vital and the exam board to have this
reinstalled and we are now at the point of requesting further access keys
from the exam board. Is it possible to find out why/how this removal
occurred in the first place in order for preventative steps to be put in
place so it doesn't happen again. This system is needed to bring in exam
results over the Summer. Our admin team aren't all year round and only come
in for the exam results and therefore if it is removed again we won't be
aware until that day. The impact of this happening will be huge.

[required] Title: Fwd: We've moving email domains, ensure you're kept in the loop!
Description:
Good Morning

Would it be possible to whitelist the emails below

Thank you


Nicola Garton

Exams Officer

Centre Number: 44143









---------- Forwarded message ---------
From: The IMI <updates@imiemail.org.uk>
Date: Tue, 27 Jun 2023 at 16:37
Subject: We've moving email domains, ensure you're kept in the loop!
To: <n.garton@asa.hslt.academy>


*Home <https://imiemail.org.uk/58VH-Q8A5-46X9R8-KL693-1/c.aspx>  Contact Us
<Hello@theimi.org.uk>*

Dear Nicola,


The IMI are making the move onto a new email domain as part of our Digital
Transformation project to deliver you a more personalised and dynamic
digital experience.


To ensure you're kept in the loop and don't miss out on any updates there
are some simple actions you need to take today.

*Whitelist via Gmail* <#m_-7005588646686962423_GMAIL>

*Whitelist via Outlook* <#m_-7005588646686962423_OUTLOOK>

*Whitelist via Yahoo* <#m_-7005588646686962423_YAHOO>

*How to Whitelist an Email in Gmail:*

If you’re using Gmail as your email provider, it’s easy to set things up so
that the IMI are whitelisted for all future communications. The Gmail
whitelist process can be done quickly via their web client:



   1. Click the settings button (*in the top-right corner of the screen*),
   then select Settings from the  drop-down menu.
   2. Navigate to the tab labelled Filtered and Blocked Addresses.
   3. Select Create a new filter and enter the email: *hello@imiupdates.org.uk
   <hello@imiupdates.org.uk> *or add the domain *imiupdates.org.uk
   <http://imiupdates.org.uk>*
   4. Click Create filter to approve the new filter, then mark Never send
   to Spam to whitelist this email.


*You can also Whitelist via the Gmail app:*



   1. Open the Gmail app on your mobile or tablet device.
   2. Go to the Spam/Junk folder.
   3. Click on the latest email received from *hello@imiupdates.org.uk
   <hello@imiupdates.org.uk>*.
   4. Select the option Report not spam.

*How to Whitelist an Email in Outlook:*

Whitelisting a domain or specific email address in Outlook.com is just as
easy and works by adding the address or domain in question to a group
called Safe senders. An address that has been added to safe senders will be
pushed to your inbox regardless of your spam filters. To add an address or
domain to safe senders:



   1. Click on Settings, then View all Outlook settings.
   2. Go to Junk email, then choose Safe senders and domains or Safe
   mailing lists.
   3. Enter the email address: *hello@mepemail.imiupdates.org.uk
   <hello@mepemail.imiupdates.org.uk> *or enter the domain *imiupdates.org.uk
   <http://imiupdates.org.uk>* to Safe senders.


Alternatively, you can add an the email address *hello@imiupdates.org.uk
<hello@imiupdates.org.uk>* to your Outlook Contacts.


*Whitelisting in Outlook mobile app*

   1. Open Outlook Mobile App.
   2. Click on the latest email from *hello@imiupdates.org.uk
   <hello@imiupdates.org.uk>*.
   3. Click on the three dots in the top right corner.
   4. Click Move to focused inbox.
   5. When the pop up screen comes up, click Move this and all future
   messages.

*How to Whitelist an Email in Yahoo Mail*

If you want to move *hello@mepemailorg.uk <hello@mepemailorg.uk> *or the
domain *imiupdates.org.uk <http://imiupdates.org.uk> *to your whitelist
Yahoo Mail, the process is very simple.


As long as you have already received at least one message from
*hello@imiupdates.org.uk
<hello@imiupdates.org.uk>*, all you have to do is highlight that message in
the Bulk folder and mark it as Not Spam.


On the other hand, if you've not received and email from
*hello@imiupdates.org.uk
<hello@imiupdates.org.uk>* yet, you’ll need to go through the following
steps to whitelist our new email address:



   1. Go to the Settings icon, then click More Settings.
   2. Select Filters and press Add new filters.
   3. From here, you can enter the email *hello@imiupdates.org.uk
   <hello@imiupdates.org.uk> *or the domain *imiupdates.org.uk
   <http://imiupdates.org.uk>*.


*Whitelisting in Yahoo Mail mobile app*

   1. Open Yahoo Mail Mobile App.
   2. Click on the sidebar.
   3. Click on the Spam folder.
   4. Find an email from *hello@imiupdates.org.uk <hello@imiupdates.org.uk>*
   to whitelist.
   5. Then click Move and then click Inbox.

If you're email service provider is not listing above you can either *Google
Search: How to Whitelist and email sender on 'Enter Email Service Prover
Here'* or contact our MarComms team via *marcommsinbox@theimi.org.uk*
<marcommsinbox@theimi.org.uk> who will be more than happy to assist you
further.

Dear Mike

The KCSiE guidance for us to be compliant we need to:

   - physically monitoring by staff watching screens of users
   - live supervision by staff on a console with device management software
   - network monitoring using log files of internet traffic and web access
   - individual device monitoring through software or third-party services
   - users are identifiable to the school or college, so concerns can be
   traced back to an individual, including guest accounts
   - If mobile or app technologies are used then you should apply a
   technical monitoring system to the devices, as your filtering system might
   not pick up mobile or app content.
   - documenting decisions on what is blocked or allowed and why

KCSiE 4 areas of risk:
136. The breadth of issues classified within online safety is considerable
and ever evolving, but can be categorised into four areas of risk:
content: being exposed to illegal, inappropriate, or harmful content, for
example: pornography, fake news, racism, misogyny, self-harm, suicide,
anti-Semitism, radicalisation, and extremism.
contact: being subjected to harmful online interaction with other users;
for example: peer to peer pressure, commercial advertising and adults
posing as children or young adults with the intention to groom or exploit
them for sexual, criminal, financial or other purposes.
conduct: online behaviour that increases the likelihood of, or causes,
harm; for example, making, sending and receiving explicit images (e.g.
consensual and non consensual sharing of nudes and semi-nudes and/or
pornography, sharing other explicit images and online bullying,
commerce: risks such as online gambling, inappropriate advertising,
phishing and or financial scams. If you feel your pupils, students or staff
are at risk, please report it to the Anti-Phishing Working Group (
https://apwg.org/).

Morning Craig,
Transition week is coming up fast. It runs from Monday 10th July to Friday
14th July. You are probably aware that during that week we usually complete
our online standardised testing with all students.

There will be three tutor groups, amounting to approximately between 70 and
90 students in the Sports Hall for periods 2, 3 and 4 each day.

There are some implications for you during this week:

1. we need you to be available in the Sports Hall during periods 2, 3 and 4
each of the days of the testing, to trouble shoot etc
2. we need 90 devices (Sarah tells me we have sourced these centrally from
the Trust - can you please make sure they are in the building before the
end of next week so we can check they are compatible with the online
testing website?). These devices need to be able to be plugged into the
trolleys we have onsite at the end of each day so they start the next day
fully charged. Obviously, on the final Friday before the week itself
(Friday 7th July), they need to be left in the Sports Hall in their
trolleys so they are charging over the weekend. These trolleys need to be
left in the Sports Hall over night after each day of testing.
3. on each day of testing, the devices need to be open on exam desks and
ready to go, already logged in to the school network, so that all students
have to do is to enter their own unique code, which they will have with
them on their exam tables.

If you have any questions about this, can you please come and see me this
week?

Thanks
Lee

[required] Title: Fwd: KCSiE 2023 IT update urgent - Filtering and Monitoring
Description:
Dear Mike

Thank you for your time today. Below is the email I sent Giles - but
basically with the new KCSiE - we are not compliant with regard to
filtering and monitoring - it may be a Trust wide issue but we are
responsible as a school.

We have to ensure that all school devices - laptops, PCs, chrome books -
that we can monitor and know who is accessing what - currently smoothwall
only tells me this on microsoft machines. We also need to be able to
monitor what staff are accessing when at home on school PC's.

Jun 22, 2023, 12:11 GMT+1
Hello Nicola,

Thank you for contacting InVentry Support.

I understand your concern and would recommend you refer to the below
knowledgebase article to know more about how to install the InVentry
Console:


   - How To Install The InVentry Console On Your PC
   <https://support.inventry.co.uk/hc/en-us/articles/360012521478-How-To-Install-The-InVentry-Console-On-Your-PC>


Also, you may refer to the below option to get the different access for the
InVentry Console:

*Option 1 (If you have an admin user on site):*
In order to create your user account for the InVentry Console please pass
the following to a user with administrator access to the InVentry system:
- Log into the InVentry Console on your PC.
- Select 'Personnel' tab at the top, then select 'Records' on the left hand
side.
- Search for the staff member you would like to give access and click on
their name.
- A window will open on the right hand side, above this you will see
options (in a grey box) click this and select 'Edit record'.
- When the window opens please ensure that they have an email address
within their record (this will be their username).
- Once this has been checked select the 'Permissions' tab on the left,
enable the top permission, input a password and set any permissions that
they will require.
- When the permissions have been set, please click 'Save'.

Once all of the above has been completed the new user will now be able to
log into the InVentry Console.

For visual aid, please see the following support portal guide:

How To Set Up Console Access Permissions For Personnel
<https://inventry.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/articles/360021818693-How-To-Set-Up-Console-Access-Permissions-For-Personnel>

*Option 2 (If you do not have an admin user on site):*
In order for us to setup any account on your InVentry system we will
require written permission from either the Headteacher, Deputy Headteacher
or the Business Manager. We require this due to the InVentry Console
application giving users access to personal data. They will also need to
advise on what level of access you require.

The different levels of access are:

- Administrator. This gives you access to all sections of the InVentry
Console application including the setup and options.
- Full access. This is the same as an admin account but you do not have
access to the setup and options.
- Staff and visitor access. Can only view staff and visitor sections.
- Pupil and visitor access. Can only view pupil and visitor sections.
- Visitor access. Can only access the visitor section.

Users will only be able to view reports that are relevant to the access
they have.

If you could please ask the above person to send an email granting us
permission to setup the account and what access is required to
support@inventry.co.uk using the ticket reference 449730 as the email
subject.

Once we receive the confirmation a member of the support team will be in
contact to arrange a remote connection to your InVentry system to create
the account.

Kind regards

Manmeet Singh

From "Farrow, Leigh" <Leigh.Farrow@york.gov.uk>: Morning Debbie,

Please allow me to detail the steps that need to be taken in order for the network alarm monitoring to work.  I’m assuming the alarm panel has not been attached to the network previously, therefore all of these steps are a pre-requisite for a new system.

Vital

  *   Check data point is available for network connectivity.
  *   Ensure data point is live and patched to school network
  *   Allocate static IP address for alarm panel
  *   Notify school/G&K/CYC of allocated address & gateway

G&K

  *   Program alarm panel with allocated static IP address.
  *   Ensure alarm panel is patched into designated data outlet.

CYC

  *   Configure CYC firewall to allow outbound connectivity for alarm panel IP address.

I hope this helps identify areas of responsibility and where we currently are in achieving resolution.

Kind regards

Leigh Farrow | ICT Officer

> as well.

and then try to log in again after the password has been changed.

when you select 'My apps' on the portal.

https://userportal.pqs.pearsonprd.tech/, https://iam.pearson.com and
https://edexcelonline.pearson.com/ whitelisted on your Centre
network/firewall and then try to access the portal again. Please also
ensure that do-not-reply@pearson.com is on your allowed senders email list
so the emails do not go to your junk folder or get quarantined. The website
also connects to AWS over port 8443 during the login process, so please
check this is not blocked as it may cause the unresponsiveness on the page.

New ways to support you
With AQA you’re always supported. We know that you want a bigger voice in what we do and the decisions we make. To allow us to work closer together, we’ll be offering updates and briefings, and hosting exclusive events, so you have the opportunity to hear about our work, the policy changes and consultations affecting exam boards and their provision. You’ll also have the opportunity to contribute your views and experiences to this network.

The easiest way for you to stay informed is by signing up for updates<http://email.schoolcommunications.co.uk/rsps/m/SBG3uillnSH0keYWcUV8MM0mkgeM2vvwpxpHYXitEN0>, and by including your job title of Head of Centre or Deputy/Assistant Head, you’ll receive access to new, free online events.

Insights for SLT webinar series
As part of our support offer, later this month we’re launching a new series of Insights for SLT webinars, featuring exciting guest speakers.

Hi,

I met with our new starter today and she has hopefully handed in the new
starter pack via reception this afternoon.

- Please can she be in 8RGI (has studied Spanish, good friends with Emily
Graville in this form already who we will assign as buddy)
- Mike - if there is any scope to be in Emily's classes great. She is
shy/anxious.
- IT - please can she have classcharts/google classroom once paperwork is
processed.
- Finance - please can mum have a call re: parent pay etc once paperwork is
processed. She will also need adding onto Flamingo Land list.

I will email out TT to teachers once set up. She is looking to start next
Tuesday.

Thanks,
Jessa

*Meeting minutes below Y8 team; will add to cpoms when she is on the
system: *

Meeting with mum, Millie, cm.
- Did well academically in Y7 but has struggled at Woldgate in Y8
- Has 2 sisters, Kasey Thompson in Y10 and younger sibling at a different
school.
- Already good friends with Emily Graville & Laila(?), would prefer to be
in Emily's form
- Studies Spanish but has found this hard this year
- Some low-level bullying at Woldate - boys hitting her - but main barrier
is no lasting friendships and lack of pastoral support.
- Support so far has been being able to go to Woldgate's wellbeing room at
social times as she was spending breaks/lunches in toilets as she had no
friends, but often not staffed or she was turned away
- Has accessed Wellbeing worker at Woldgate
- Woldgate offered a phased return this week after half term to alleviate
struggles. Mum said attendance really good (99%) prior to this.
- Likes Football & Gymnastics and attends clubs for these outside school.
Favourite subjects Art/Technology. Dislikes and struggles with English.
- Millie presented as being polite/smiley in the meeting and enthusiastic
about joining the school. Millie was quiet/shy and often hid behind her
hair on the tour if we passed other students. Didn't like to be stood
within view when looking at classrooms. Quite intimidated by school size
and said she is afraid of getting lost. Buddy will be Emily and safe space
Y8 office.

What do I need to do now?
Do not attempt to open the licence file other than by using the batch import process within SIMS.net. You just need to right click on the Photo Licence file attached to this email and save it somewhere to your system.

How do I order a new licence once this one expires?
Each year you will be required to log into the ESS Portal to administer your agreement with ESS, and Photo Import Licence will be included in this, once your initial term for Photo Import Licence expires. This means that your Photo Import Licence will automatically renew and each year we will issue you with an updated Photo Import Licence automatically.

What if I wish to cancel my Photo Import licence?

We require at least 90 days written notice, prior to your next renewal date (31st March) in order to cancel your Photo Import licence. This means that notice is always due, no later than the 31st December prior to your initial contract term end date (for example, if your contract term end date is 31st March 2025, then notice is required no later than 31st December 2024). Notice must be sent, in writing to SIMSContracts@parentpay.com<mailto:SIMSContracts@parentpay.com>. If sufficient notice is not received, then your Photo Importer Licence will be automatically renewed, as per the Terms outlined in the ESS Portal when this becomes available to you.

Who should I contact for support?
Distribution are unable to provide technical support; if you require support, please contact our Service Desk on:-

E: support@educationsoftwaresolutions.co.uk<mailto:support@educationsoftwaresolutions.co.uk>
